english:
  title: A Memorial Opposing Buddhism
  author: Park Cho
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty, we humbly consider that since our Sage Ancestor founded this realm, the golden branches and jade leaves of succession have been transmitted unbroken for nearly five hundred years. Though we suffered the darkness of usurpation by foreign houses—sorrows too grievous to voice—Your Majesty has arrived with divine sagacity, responding to Heaven's mandate and the people's longing. Without drawing sword or spear, you have swept away treachery, restored our ancestral shrines, and brought forth an age of harmony. The billions of the Three Lands rejoiced, wiped their eyes in wonder, and gazed toward universal peace. This is the true restoration of ancient virtue and the renewal of our realm's glory.

    We scholars, blessed to witness this enlightened age, entered the halls of learning yet squandered our stipends in idleness. Overwhelmed by Your Majesty's grace, we have long harbored the ambition to embody the governance of Yao and Shun, to reject heterodox doctrines. Yet without position and without path, we could not act. Indignation filled our hearts; we sighed in shadows. If our words might reach your ear and awaken your wisdom, we would accept any punishment without regret. How much more now, when Your Majesty has issued virtuous proclamations and opened wide the path of remonstrance, seeking counsel as one thirsts for water? How dare we remain silent and betray a lifetime's resolve? We beseech Your Majesty to extend yet greater tolerance, that this enlightened court harbor no sage whose forthright words bring death. Such mercy would be the fortune of our realm.

    We have heard it said: there is Heaven and Earth, then the ten thousand things; there are the ten thousand things, then male and female; there are male and female, then husband and wife; there is husband and wife, then father and son; there is father and son, then ruler and minister; there is ruler and minister, then superior and inferior; there is superior and inferior, then propriety and righteousness find their place. This is the universal way of Heaven and Earth, the constant principle of all ages, not to be abandoned even for a moment. Should any abandon it, the cosmos itself would not contain them; sun and moon would refuse to shine upon them; spirits would join to strike them down; the judgment of all people throughout all ages would condemn them.

    What manner of man is this Buddha? A favored son who betrayed his father, sundering the bond between parent and child. A commoner who defied the Son of Heaven, destroying the righteousness between ruler and subject. He declared that a man and woman sharing household to be contrary to the Way, that man tilling soil and woman spinning thread to be wickedness. Thus he severed the path of generation itself and blocked the sources of clothing and sustenance. Should his doctrine prevail over all beneath Heaven, then within a hundred years humankind would cease to exist. Heaven moves above, Earth sustains below, and between them life springs forth. Yet if this came to pass, only grasses, trees, beasts, fishes, and serpents would remain. Where then could the Three Bonds and Five Relationships find dwelling?

    Buddha himself was born among the barbarians, speaking a tongue unlike the Middle Kingdom's, wearing garments of foreign make. His mouth uttered none of the ancient kings' teachings; his body wore none of their vestments. He knew nothing of the relationships between husband and wife, father and son, ruler and subject. He falsely opened the Three Evil Paths and grotesquely magnified the Six Realms of Existence, causing the foolish to chase empty merit-making, to disregard prohibition and law, to violate the very codes of governance.

    Yet life and death arise from nature; prosperity and calamity rest with the ruler; poverty and wealth are fruits of one's deeds—these things are constant. The false monks, through deception, claim all comes from Buddha, thus stealing the ruler's authority, arrogating the power of creation itself, obscuring the people's sight and understanding, plunging all beneath Heaven into murk and delusion. People live drunk and dream their deaths away, never waking. For this they erect towers, halls, palaces, and gates, adorned with earthen and wooden forms, copper and iron statues, filling them with the shorn and bound of both sexes. Their splendor surpasses even Jie's Jade Palace or Zhou's Jeweled Tower, yet all this wealth flows from the people's labor and substance. Alas, what sorrow! Who shall correct this?

    Only when those above perfect virtue within themselves and transform those below through teaching, illuminating propriety and righteousness so that our people know where Heaven's principle resides—only then can it be corrected. Our Eastern Land received Buddhism from late Silla's era, until temples and pagodas filled even the villages. Buddhist teachings flowed abundantly into ears, seeped into flesh, penetrated the very marrow. Principle and reason could not awaken them; words could not convince them.

    When our Taejo unified the Three Lands, he deeply learned from accumulated evils and forbade later rulers and ministers to privately build temples. Thus Grand Preceptor Choe Gyeong requested the elimination of Buddhist law. Yet Taejo said: "In late Silla, Buddhist doctrine entered people's very marrow. All believe that life, death, fortune, and calamity spring from Buddha. Now that the Three Lands are barely unified and hearts not yet settled, if we suddenly reject Buddhism, we will surely provoke alarm." He therefore established a teaching: "Take as mirror how Silla multiplied Buddhist works until its ruin came." How profound and urgent was Taejo's instruction to posterity!

    Yet successive rulers and ministers, failing to grasp our Sage Ancestor's intent, have drifted and compromised, building hermitages and erecting pagodas without end. The evils multiply daily. How can those concerned with people's hearts and the state's way not grieve?

    The classic teaches: "Should one man not till, some will hunger. Should one woman not spin, some will freeze." Yet Buddhist monks, without tilling, feast abundantly; without spinning, wear fine robes. Millions live in idle comfort while countless freeze and starve.

    Though these monks might subsist on wind and dew, dwelling in trees and wilderness, the state should expel them. How much more those who sit in splendid halls, eat refined fare, move their hands in lazy gestures, and bow to rulers and parents? Such beings cannot dwell one day beneath Heaven—they are enemies of all creation.

    Yet Your Majesty, possessed of brilliant wisdom, has been beguiled by monks' superstitious prophecies, traveling south to personally visit Hyean Temple with imperial dignity, championing teachings that deny father and ruler, establishing customs of disloyalty and impiety, undermining our Three Bonds and Five Relationships. We grieve for the beauty of Your Majesty's restoration.

    On the day of your birth, Your Majesty should have led all officials to present wishes of longevity to the Queen Mother, displaying your filial virtue to all the realm. Instead, you reverse course, following barbarian teachings, humbly bowing to monks and serving Buddha, thus thwarting your subjects' hopes for righteous renewal. How is this acceptable?

    Furthermore, your demands exhaust the people's strength and gather their resentment for pagoda-building projects. The realm cries out in anguish; scholars and commons despair. We know not whether the timber materializes through ghostly transport or the funds rain down from Heaven and spring from Earth. You seek blessings in unseen realms yet invite calamities in the visible world.

    Should wind and dust soon rise again, should frost and hail descend repeatedly, monks cannot wield spear or shield, nor can pagodas dispel famine. In ages past, Northern Zhou destroyed Buddhist scriptures and images to strengthen its armies, while Qi exalted temples yet relaxed punishments. In a single day of battle, Zhou prospered and Qi perished. Thus we see that Buddha cannot bestow fortune or curse upon the human realm.

    We beseech Your Majesty to follow the ways by which Yao, Shun, and the Three Dynasties flourished, taking as mirror why Qi, Chen, and Liang fell. Above, inherit our Sage Ancestor's design; below, fulfill the scholars' ancient hopes. Return these Buddhists to their native lands. Make their people our people for military service; build homes where temples stood to increase our population. Burn their writings to sever their roots forever. Let military officials manage their fields to provision armies. Let state officials oversee their slaves to distribute among our agencies. Assign their bronze images and vessels to the Military Armory to strengthen our forces. Distribute their implements among the various bureaus.

    Then teach them through propriety and nurture them through virtue. Within years the people's hearts will stabilize, transformation will succeed, granaries will overflow, and state resources will flourish. Those who once rejected father and ruler, destroyed human bonds, and violated Heaven's principle will cast off their old stains and recover their innate goodness. They will understand the relationships between father and son, ruler and subject, and the proper ways between husband and wife. With men tilling and women spinning, they will flourish in life. Content with simple fare, they will rejoice in peace. Then the prosperity of good governance will rival the Three Dynasties and surpass even Han and Tang.

    Now the flattering minister Kim Jeon, through base character and ignorant counsel, distorts right and wrong to please Your Majesty, promoting teachings without father or ruler to abandon the sage wisdom of all ages. He claims that Taejo's founding was wholly due to Buddha's power, calling those who oppose Buddhism criminals against our founder. Yet Taejo's sacred virtue and divine accomplishment responded to Heaven and accorded with humanity. His mind matched Yao and Shun; his conduct mirrored Tang and Wu. The Three Lands' people feared his majesty as they fear thunder; they loved his virtue as they love their parents.

    Even if we had slaughtered all monks within our borders as Northern Wei did, even if we had melted all Buddha images into coins as Emperor Shizong of Zhou did, how could Buddha have prevented Taejo from unifying the Three Lands?

    Before the years Gyeongín and Gyeongsa, our realm possessed more accomplished scholars than the Middle Kingdom itself. Tang called us "the land of gentlemen," and Song called us "the realm of ritual and music, culture and civilization," inscribing at our envoys' lodging "the Hall of Lesser China." Yet after those years, unless slain by warfare, scholars fled to mountains. Scarcely one in a hundred remained. Those who study Buddha have fabricated lies, deceiving officials above and common folk below, creating nine statues of Taejo's previous incarnations, claiming he was once a temple abbot, once built a pagoda, once composed a sutra, and even became an ox at a certain temple before being reborn to claim the throne, later becoming a bodhisattva. They carved these tales in books, hid them in mountain depths to deceive ten thousand ages.

    When Emperor Seongjong saw them, he deeply revered and believed, attending lectures at the Inner Buddhist Hall and the Manjusri Assembly at Yeonbok Temple, enduring monks' sermons and feasts despite his imperial dignity, bowing to shaved monks as teachers, performing a disciple's obeisance. Yet by the year Gapín, he received no blessing from Buddhist practice. We know not whether Sakyamuni and Bodhidharma returned to the East and personally witnessed Taejo in Heaven's Buddhist realm to carve these statues, nor which monk personally saw Taejo when he was ox or temple abbot.

    These false tales deceive the ruler, portraying Taejo as an ox—can such words be uttered by a sacred heir and divine descendant?

    Alas, since right learning lacks clarity and human hearts lack rectitude, people abandon virtue-cultivation to seek mere fortune, abandon understanding of the Way to crave mere marvels. Is this not heartbreaking? Is this not lamentable?

    Since Mencius rejected Yang Zhu and Mo Di to exalt Confucius, figures like Dong Zhongshu of Han, Han Yu of Tang, and Cheng Yi and Zhu Xi of Song upheld this teaching and rejected heterodoxy, becoming exemplars for all ages. Yet Wang Anshi and Zhang Tianjue promoted Buddhism and altered customs, becoming cautionary tales for all ages. If these figures—both the exemplars Dong, Han, Cheng, and Zhu alongside the cautionaries Wang and Zhang—were all born today, would Your Majesty follow Dong, Han, Cheng, and Zhu to be the model for ten thousand ages? Or would you follow Wang and Zhang to promulgate the teachings of barbarians and beasts? We dare not presume to know.

    If Your Majesty follows what Wang Anshi and Zhang Tianjue favored, shaving the Three Lands' people into monks, casting aside nation and family, discarding the throne like worn sandals to seek Buddha in mountains, then accept Kim Jeon's counsel. But if you follow Dong, Han, Cheng, and Zhu to rectify hearts, illuminate relationships, expel the people's parasites, restore the Three Dynasties' governance, and make your restoration's works shine eternally with Heaven—then Kim Jeon should be executed in the market square to show all ages that your realm's great sage is not deceived by false teachings.

    If Your Majesty deems Kim Jeon loyal to the state, could he have saved the Wang house when Shin U and Shin Chang extinguished Taejo and thirty other sovereigns' sacrifices? Yet the Grand Rector Jeong Dojeon has illuminated the source of Heaven, humanity, nature, and fate. He proclaims the ways of Confucius, Mencius, Cheng, and Zhu, penetrating Buddhism's thousand ages of deception, opening the Three Lands' eternal blindness, silencing heterodoxy and false teachings, clarifying Heaven's principle and rectifying human hearts. In our Eastern Land, he alone exists as such a person. This is Heaven granting Your Majesty the assistance of sage ministers to establish the flourishing of Yao, Shun, and the Three Dynasties in this age of restoration.

    Does Your Majesty deem Jeong Dojeon's strategy to reject Buddhism a crime against our ancestors? Or do you deem Kim Jeon's devotion to Buddha your loyal minister? We dare not know. If Your Majesty doubts Jeong Dojeon's right learning and believes Kim Jeon's false teachings, would you not invite ridicule from all lands and contempt from all ages? This is why we dare speak.

    What else corrects the foundation of governance save rectifying human hearts? For if people's hearts lack proper direction, their foundation crumbles. Though one busies oneself with superficial matters, all becomes mere pretense. No one has ever seen a murky source yield clear waters, nor a weak root bear flourishing branches. Thus we offer alone the rejection of heterodoxy as the foundation of rectifying hearts.

    We beseech Your Majesty, amid your manifold duties, to give this particular thought. Should you take it to heart and implement it, this will bring fortune not merely to this age but lasting regard throughout ten thousand ages. If Your Majesty does not deem our words pedantic but takes them to heart, we would further expound for Your Majesty even one ten-thousandth of the Way of right governance.
